So this is precisely the fundamental string limit.


S-brane description and T-duality 

At this stage it is very natural to ask, "What is the boosted
S-brane without taking the fundamental string limit (
vanishing Lagrangian limit)?" To approach a possible answer to
this question, let us observe what happens to the orthogonal
matrix in the boundary state.  For simplicity we examine the
static case. The boundary state of a static  string
presented in Ref.  is defined through its
orthogonal matrix
 
where . Here of course  should be less than or
equal to 1. On the other hand, the boosted S1-brane with the
static limit  is also described by the above matrix
with . To relate these two descriptions, we see that if
perform the transformation
 
then the matrix  transforms as
 
Interestingly, this means that the case with electric field 
larger than 1 is related to an  smaller than 1 only by a sign
change of . The change in the sign of 
 is equivalent to the replacement 
 which is a T-duality along  and 
directions, see Eq. ().

So what we have found here is that the description of  larger
than 1 can be obtained by T-duality along  and . Let
us discuss the meaning of this duality more. Before examining our
present case, it is instructive to remember the ordinary
T-duality along spatial directions for D-branes.
Let us consider a bound state of  D0-branes and 
D2-branes. The D2-brane worldvolume is extended along  and
. The density of the D0-branes per unit area on the
worldvolume of a single D2-brane is just the magnetic field
induced on the D2-brane, . The open string boundary
condition becomes a mixed boundary condition. Now let us take a
T-duality along  and . First, T-dualizing along 
transforms this D2-D0 bound state to a D1-brane winding the 12
torus  times along  and  times along . Second,
take the T-duality along . We then get a bound state of 
D2-branes and  D0-branes, giving an induced magnetic field
. This shows that the inversion
of the magnetic field can be understood as T-duality.

Let us apply this well-known idea to our case, and see what
happens to a  string when we T-dualize along
 and . Consider a static  string
stretched along the  direction. The induced electric field
 parametrizes the number of bound fundamental
strings.  First let us take a T-duality along . The
resultant configuration is a D0-brane moving at the speed  which does
not exceed the speed of
light. This moving D0-brane can be thought of as a "winding"
D0-brane, that is, a D0-brane winding  times along  and
 time along . The winding along  should be thought of as
an S0-brane since the worldvolume is only along this spatial
direction. Now
take a second T-duality along . The former 
D0-brane becomes  S(-1)-branes, while the latter S0-brane
becomes a single D1-brane. Therefore, after the T-dualities,
we have a bound state of a single D1-brane and 
S(-1)-branes. This statement is very plausible in view of how we
derived the boosted S-brane: there we considered an S1-brane with
magnetic field , that is exactly a bound state of an
S1-brane and S(-1)-branes.  If we consider now the boosted S-brane so the
S1-brane is timelike, i.e. a D1-brane, the resultant
object should be a bound state of a D1-brane and S(-1)-branes.

Since the S-brane description in the previous subsections is valid
for , the case  is the only overlapping region and
has two equivalent descriptions. However, the above observation
leads us to an intriguing conjecture:  Any  string can be
thought of as a bound state of a D1-brane and  S(-1)-branes
with .  Here we do not specify how the latter bound state
should be described but there might be some advantages in
treating the  strings from the S-brane point of view. To
illustrate this point, consider the RR coupling on a D-brane
 
Let us turn on a constant
electric field . Usually this is said to turn the D-brane
into an (F, D) bound state, but what does
the above RR coupling tell us? The second term gives
 
This is a source term for the RR -form with spatial
indices, or in other words for an S-brane. This
suggests that the fundamental strings can be thought of as smeared
S-branes, at least in the worldvolume of other mother D-branes in
which the fundamental strings are bound.


Relation between S- and D-brane descriptions 

In the above we have learned that while D-branes with small
electric fields are described by D-brane actions, D-branes with
large electric fields are described by S-brane actions. Following
the previous subsection, here we further explore the T-duality
which interchanges these two classes of configurations.

For simplicity, only the electric field
in the  direction is turned on.
The Lagrangian, electric flux density
and the Hamiltonian for the D-brane are given by
 
and those for the S-brane are
 
The range of electric fields valid for the D-brane description is
, which is mapped to the range of validity  for
the S-brane description by the T-duality along the time direction
 
considered in the previous subsection. From
the expressions above,
we find that this map induces
the interchange of  and ,
or equivalently the interchange of
the fundamental string charge and the energy.
Recall that ordinary T-duality interchanges
winding modes with Kaluza-Klein modes.
Since the total string number can be thought of
as the "winding number",
and the energy as the "momentum" in the time direction,
roughly speaking, the interchange of  and 
is what one would expect for the T-duality in the time direction.



Boosted S3-brane as a D-string 

Earlier in this section we saw how the late time part of the
solution of Section  can be realized as a boosted
S1-brane. We may expect that in the same manner the late time
configuration of the spike solution of Section  can also
be obtained as a boosted S-brane. Here we will present a boosted
solution of an S3-brane action with magnetic fields,(Though so
far in this section we have used S1-branes, in this subsection
we need magnetic fields and so use an S3-brane instead.)  and show
that actually the boundary state of the boosted S3-brane reduces
to that of a static D-string.

