Tachyonic S-brane Action 

In this appendix, we explicitly demonstrate how the tachyonic
S-branes considered in Section  appear in the tachyon
condensation of D-brane anti-D-brane. In Fig. ,
this is the arrow (2). Since the arrow (1) has already been
discussed in Ref. , while the arrow (3) is just the
same as the usual D-brane descent relation, and the arrow (4) was
realized in Section , the derivation of (2) completes
the explanation of the generalized descent relations of
Fig. .

To derive the effective action of the "tachyonic S-brane" by
using the fluctuation analysis of the time dependent kink as
performed in Ref. , we return to the Lagrangian of
the D- pair in Eq. () and the solution
representing  the tachyonic S-brane in Eq. (). A
direct analysis of this fluctuation mode is difficult due to the
complexity of the Lagrangian.

The easiest way to proceed is to simplify the situation and
truncate the derivatives of the Lagrangian at fourth order
 
where  and  are numerical constants.
We must keep at least fourth order derivative terms since if we
only keep the usual canonical kinetic energy there are no tachyon
solution linear in time, and unless the solution is linear it is
again technically difficult to perform a fluctuation analysis.
The equation of motion for a homogeneous time dependent
tachyon is
 
where , and we have set . Therefore the
linear solution
 
exits for .

It is actually strange that we have completely linear solution in
spite of the presence of the tachyon potential. The higher-order
kinetic term makes this situation possible. The general solution
does not exhibit the rolling tachyon behavior at late time, since
this model is just a generalization of the Minahan-Zwiebach model
which does not possess the rolling tachyon behavior. The general
solution reaches the true vacuum  in finite time. But
if we tune the initial condition then we have the completely
linear solution for the rolling tachyon. The strangeness of this
solution is also apparent in that its energy vanishes
 
For the meantime we treat this special solution as just an
illustration of the new descent relations.




Fluctuation spectrum 

Let us consider the following fluctuation
 
where . Substituting this into the action and
collecting terms quadratic in the fluctuation fields, we obtain
the fluctuation action
 
The two fluctuation modes are completely decoupled from each
other.  Integrating by parts, we find that
 
To see the physical meaning of these fluctuations, we redefine
the fields as  so the
newly defined fields  have canonical kinetic
terms. Then we can decompose the fields 
into the eigenfunctions of the harmonic potential along , as
performed in Ref. .   We may determine the "mass"
spectra for these fluctuations as the eigenvalues of the
Laplacian, , for the spatial directions.

The  fluctuation contains a zero mode which is the Nambu-Goldstone
mode
associated with the symmetry breaking of the translation along
 by the presence of the kink solution. The 'mass' tower of
 is obtained as
 
The constant  should be less than  to keep the
coefficient of the term  negative.

Next, we use the field redefinitions to rewrite the action 
as
 
 From this expression it is easy to extract the mass spectrum
 
Here again  should be satisfied so that the
fluctuation Lagrangian is positive definite. The lowest mode
becomes tachyonic, and this tachyonic mode is associated with the
instability of the time-dependent kink solution.





Effective action 

The lowest modes in the fluctuations 
are Gaussian, and if one expresses these in term of the original
fluctuation then they are actually constant, independent of
. Using this property, we can calculate the effective action
for the tachyonic S-brane. By substitution of the fluctuation
into the original D- action, we have
 
(In the last line we have performed the integration over .)
This is the tachyonic S-brane effective action, which resembles a
Minahan-Zwiebach model.
The difference between them are as
follows: (1) the sign of  term  is negative,
indicating that this mode represents the translation along the
time direction. (2) the worldvolume metric defining this theory
is Euclidean. These two properties are shared with the S-brane
action obtained in our previous paper.

Although we have adopted a derivative truncation as the starting
point () and also a special solution
(), we believe that this effective action
() may capture essential features of the tachyonic
S-branes.


