Let us consider higher order terms in the Hamiltonian to see the
localization of the energy which should correspond to the energy of the
boosted S-brane.
In the limit (), it turns out
that the next-to-leading order term coming
from the expansion of the potential term 
can be ignored.
First, we expand the function  for large  at
 as
 
Then the Hamiltonian is
evaluated to the next-to-leading order as
 
Here
the second term in the first
line is from the higher order evaluation of 
in (), while
the second line comes from evaluation of  term in the
Hamiltonian ().
Interestingly, though these two exponential terms
become infinitely small in the limit ,
they are combined and approach a  function whose coefficient is
finite. More
precisely, the above expression is arranged in this limit as
 
So, in addition to the homogeneous energy of the background rolling
tachyon, we have a localized energy with a finite coefficient!
This second term should be identified with the energy of the boosted
S1-brane.

We now show that the localized energy contribution we just
calculated agrees with the Hamiltonian of the S1-brane action.
The action of a static S1-brane located at  is
 
Using this action, one finds that
the S1-brane Hamiltonian density is
 
Now this electric field  is the induced electric field as seen
in Eq. (). After taking the limit
, we have .
Substituting this into the S-brane Hamiltonian (), we
obtain
 
Remarkably this agrees with the finite energy contribution in
Eq. () using the S-brane tension of
Eq. ()!

Lastly we provide a comment on this localized energy. In the final
expression (), the S-brane contribution was
found to be negative. This suggests that the S-brane has a
negative energy, which agrees with the result of the boundary
state analysis in which the time-time component of the boosted
S-brane boundary state is given by a negative value as opposed to
the usual boundary states for  strings.  In this appendix
we have shown why this does not result in any of the usual
problems.  While the contribution of the S-brane is negative,
there is an additional leading order energy contribution in
Eq. ()
which is due to the energy of the background
rolling tachyon,
and so the total energy is still positive.

The picture is reminiscent of anti-particles in the "Dirac sea".
The boosted S-brane is like something existing in a cloud of
fundamental strings. Since our non-BPS D-brane formulation did
not take care of the radiation of the fundamental strings, it
keeps the energy and effect of all these strings which are
supposed to radiate away. (One of the effects of this cloud of
fundamental strings might possibly be to make the S-brane
energy negative.)
Actually, the string cloud will dissipate, and the S-brane with
strings attached to it will become a D-brane with strings
attached to it.
(Here we have to distinguish the strings on
the non-BPS D-brane which will decay away,
from strings stuck to the S-brane.)
As a final remark,
the energy of the background rolling tachyon
in () diverges in the limit
. The validity of
some of the calculations are not so rigorous
due to this singular limit. Although the boosted S-brane is expected to
capture the late time behaviour of the spike solution in
Section , apparently this divergence
comes from the fact that we have
not taken into account the curved worldvolume of the S-brane in the
spike solution where  is divergent only at . In this
sense the correspondence between the spike solution and the boosted
S-brane is not exact.





